SIMPLE: sulphurous
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sulphurous
<hw>Sul"phur*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>sulphurosus</ets>, <ets>sulfurosus</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>sulfureux</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to
sulphur.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Derived from, or
containing, sulphur; specifically, designating those compounds in which
the element has a lower valence as contrasted with the
<xex>sulphuric</xex> compounds.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Having the
characteristic odor of sulphur dioxide, or of hydrogen sulphide, or of
other sulphur compounds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sulphurous acid</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>Sulphur
dioxide. See under <er>Sulphur</er>.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>An acid, <chform>H2SO3</chform>, not known in the free
state except as a solution of sulphur dioxide in water, but forming a
well-known series of salts (the <xex>sulphites</xex>).</cd> --
<col><b>Sulphurous anhydride</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>sulphur
dioxide. See under <er>Sulphur</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sulphurwort</ent>⟦br⟧
